I'm using cocos2d 3.7.1. It's recommended in documentation to "end" AudioEngine before the app exits, so Here is what I did:

```
AppDelegate::~AppDelegate() 
{
    cocos2d::experimental::AudioEngine::end();
}
```

But that line results in an exception being thrown on line 95 of "AudioEngine-win32.cpp". On that line AudioEngineThreadPool is trying to join all threads running, to safely exit the application. It's "std::system_exception" error, caused by threads not being joinable.

```
void destroy()
{
    _running = false;
    _sleepCondition.notify_all();

    for (int index = 0; index < _numThread; ++index) {
        _threads[index].join();
    }
}           
```

After digging more into the code, I've found this, inside AudioEngineThreadPool constructor (line 65 of same file):

```
_threads.reserve(_numThread);
_tasks.reserve(_numThread);

for (int index = 0; index < _numThread; ++index) {
    _tasks.push_back(nullptr);
    _threads.push_back( std::thread( std::bind(&AudioEngineThreadPool::threadFunc,this,index) ) );
    _threads[index].detach();
}
```

On line 65, all threads are detached, meaning they are no longer joinable. But in destroy function, it tries to join all those threads, even though they are detached aka. non-joinable; Which according to C++ specification should throw system_error exception [[reference]](http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/thread/thread/join/)

Potential fixes:
1. Remove detach from line 65
2. check if thread is joinable, before joining it on line 95

I see a strange thing when working with Scenes in Cocos2d-x. Any transformation of this container (e.g. moving, scaling, etc) shows that it's rendered twice: without transformations and with them as well.
Here's a simple graph of my example application:
globalScene (Scene) -> levelScene (a subclass of Scene) -> rootScene (a Scene to which my nodes are added)
And here's the code:

```
bool LevelScene::init() {
        if (!Scene::init()) {
            return false;
        }

        this->rootScene = Scene::create();

        auto square = Sprite::create("dirt.jpg");
        square->setPosition(Vec2(100, 100));

        this->rootScene->addChild(square);


        // some code from tutorials
        auto eventListener = EventListenerKeyboard::create();

        eventListener->onKeyPressed = [](EventKeyboard::KeyCode keyCode, Event* event){

        Vec2 loc = event->getCurrentTarget()->getPosition();
        switch (keyCode) {
        case EventKeyboard::KeyCode::KEY_LEFT_ARROW:
        case EventKeyboard::KeyCode::KEY_A:
            event->getCurrentTarget()->setPosition(--loc.x, loc.y);
            break;
        case EventKeyboard::KeyCode::KEY_RIGHT_ARROW:
        case EventKeyboard::KeyCode::KEY_D:
            event->getCurrentTarget()->setPosition(++loc.x, loc.y);
            break;
        case EventKeyboard::KeyCode::KEY_UP_ARROW:
        case EventKeyboard::KeyCode::KEY_W:
            event->getCurrentTarget()->setPosition(loc.x, ++loc.y);
            break;
        case EventKeyboard::KeyCode::KEY_DOWN_ARROW:
        case EventKeyboard::KeyCode::KEY_S:
            event->getCurrentTarget()->setPosition(loc.x, --loc.y);
            break;
        }
    };

    _eventDispatcher->addEventListenerWithSceneGraphPriority(eventListener, this->rootScene);

    this->addChild(rootScene);

    return true;
}
```

